`SysProperties` could be initialized by H2. This seems like a complex relationship between these components, and I want to make sure I’ve got everything lined up correctly!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering test setup options**\\n\\nI'm thinking about using `@BeforeAll` with `System.setProperty` in the H2Test to set the property before DriverManager is utilized. But I'm wrestling with whether modifying an unrelated test is the best approach. Maybe I can add a static block in H2Test to set the property instead. That could be a broader solution without directly affecting the existing test structure. Just trying to weigh the pros and cons here!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating JVM behavior**\\n\\nI'm considering the JVM test run where `clinit` uses reflection for nested serializers and records, which seems good. But, if I'm under a native image, the system property specifies the nested class name containing `$`. It includes test classes, which is fine. However, I need to think about whether the user's code filter will exclude test packages. I guess it would be wise to read more about that and clarify any related issues.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_UFXNo0WcsOJgsfYqVv8uXu5k|fc_063f40c823398bca0169f9129c597c819e9b67caff3627453d", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/com.h2database/h2/2.1.210/user-code-filter.json"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1939, "output": 1346, "cacheRead": 17920, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 21205, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1777930886903, "responseId": "resp_063f40c823398bca0169f9128761b8819e8f09b214e205615c"}}
